description.value: Clay figure made of a brown fine clay that was lightly fired and consolidated after excavation resulting in a darker surface colour. The object itself is very crudely formed, roughly horizontally cylindrical with slightly pointed ends. One end has been pinched together and curls slightly upwards. From the other end another piece would have been run off but is broken off. A small, horizontal slit appears on one side, its outer end was formed out of the main body part still showing three small (children) finger impressions on each side of the slit. The slit itself measures 1.05 x 0.2 cm and has a depth of about 2.2 cm, maybe another (part of an) object was attached here. The object could have been a stylized animal figurine.

description.value: Wooden female figure: when it was new, this wooden statuette would have been fully painted to show the two straps of the woman's white dress, perhaps a necklace, and most probably her name, on the base. The figure stands with her feet together and her open hands at her sides. The palms, however, do not face her body, but are turned toward the back in a reverential or prayerful gesture. Her narrow torso, wasp waist, bony hips, and long, swelling thighs represent the ideal of female beauty in the Middle Kingdom. In this case, the effect is fairly natural. It is startling to turn from the stylish, youthful body to its stern, heavy, mature-looking face. The face of this woman is based on the portrait features and expressions of Senusret III or Amenemhat III. Her narrowed, hooded eyes and full cheeks indicate that the model for this statue was Amenemhat III, rather than Senusret III.

description.value: Terracotta figure of a satyr offering a wineskin. This well preserved terracotta shows the figure of a young satyr kneeling on the ground and clutching a large skin. The colour is extremely well preserved and the tanned skin of the satyr is easily distinguished from the red skin that he holds and the ochre cloak, which flares behind him. The hair is unkempt and the head thrown backwards, giving the impression that the satyr is looking upwards as he holds out the skin, presumably to receive its contents. The slovenly way in which he is seated might suggest drunkenness, and it has been suggested that the subject shown is part of a Dionysiac festival and that the skin is held out to catch wine. Light red clay with a yellow surface and a yellow-white slip. Black, red and brown painted decoration. Mould-made.

description.value:
Limestone fragmentary head of a female figure.

She wears a heavy tripartite style wig with a centre parting and detailed striations across the individual tresses of hair. The ends of the wig are now lost, and the left side has broken off in a roughly diagonal line from the chin. Her eyes are narrow and her thin eyebrows are modelled in raised relief. The outline of her nose suggests this was broad in size, and there is a clear cupid’s bow above her top lip. Her mouth is upturned to suggest a small smile, and her lower lip is sharply incised. On the reverse much of the head and wig is now lost.

The nose has been damaged, and there are also small chips across the face and neck. On the reverse is a small drilled hole towards the right side.

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone kneeling figure of the king Hakor, the upper body now lost.

The figure wears a short shendyt kilt and is shown with the knees placed close together and the feet flexed. On top of the kilt is a rounded sunken area of the stone that likely featured an object held by the king, which is now lost. A broken outline shows that his arms were held out towards this damaged area on his lap. On both legs and feet are traces of a white colour, with faint traces of a faded darker colour on the right side ankle. On the reverse, the lower section of a slim back-pillar bears traces of painted text including the cartouches of the king.

In addition to the damaged torso section, the right side of the base is heavily damaged and there are chips to the surface across the knees and kilt.

description.value: Light grey limestone head of a kouros figure, painted.  Head of a young man, broken at the base of the neck from a statuette. The right cheek and earlobe are damaged.  The face is oval with a pointed chin, a long aquiline nose, wide protruding eyes; the eyebrows and the outline of the eyes show traces of black paint. The mouth is small and shaped into a smile, with traces of red paint; a moustache was rendered in relief and painted in black, a full beard was indicated from the temples down to the upper edge of the neck by means of black spots.  The hair is worked as a flat mass parted in the centre and falling like a wig down to the neck; the ears are not covered and rawly treated. There are traces of black paint on the hair; on the forehead a thin red headband was painted right below the hairline. The back is worked flat.

description.value: Wooden male figure: the face is idealized; the smile is derived ultimately from the benign curve in the lips of Amenhotep III, whose slight smile was emulated during the Amarna Period, at the end of the Eighteenth Dynasty, and eventually on some representations of Ramses II in the Nineteenth Dynasty. The man's costume places him in the last decades of the Eighteenth Dynasty or the first years of the Nineteenth. He wears a double wig, shirt, and kilt. The front sections of the double wig comprise large, full bunches of curls, spilling down onto the chest. The shirtsleeves were now much long, wide, and floppy. The kilt is entirely pleated, and the tucking and flouncing of its front panel is intricate. He was originally painted.

description.value:
Black steatite figure of the god Thoth seated upon a tall plinth.

Thoth is depicted as a seated baboon and he wears the lunar-disc crown. The tip of the horns on either side of the crown are now lost. The fur around the head and ‘feathered hood’ or layers of fur of the chest are conveyed through detailed thin incisions. His front paws are placed on the knees, and his tail curled around the right side hind leg. He sits on top of a tall pedestal topped with a cornice, and with a double flight of steps incised on the front.

The top left side of his head has been damaged, and the cornice and staircase at the front of the pedestal is chipped. The lower right side portion of the staircase is also lost. There are large scratches to the stone surface around the sides of the pedestal.

Black steatite figure of the god Thoth seated upon a tall plinth.

Thoth is depicted as a seated baboon and he wears the lunar-disc crown. The tip of the horns on either side of the crown are now lost. The fur around the head and ‘feathered hood’ or layers of fur of the chest are conveyed through detailed thin incisions. His front paws are placed on the knees, and his tail curled around the right side hind leg. He sits on top of a tall pedestal topped with a cornice, and with a double flight of steps incised on the front.

The top left side of his head has been damaged, and the cornice and staircase at the front of the pedestal is chipped. The lower right side portion of the staircase is also lost. There are large scratches to the stone surface around the sides of the pedestal.

description.value: Glazed composition amuletic figure: a superbly modelled, dog faced baboon, in an apple green glazed composition, squats on a low plinth with curved back, that fits into a like shaped depression on the top of a long base that has a double stepped ramp at its front. He carries before him, supported by one paw and steadied by the other, a 'wedjat' eye. The details of his characteristically shaped features, his cheek fur, heavy mane, his long tail curved beside his right foot and his sexual member are all carefully delineated. There is a ring for suspension behind his shoulders. Although the base into which the baboon is now inset is of the same coloured material, and the depression into which it is inset is of the correct shape, it is not a snug fit. It cannot be certain that this particular amulet and base were together originally. Nevertheless, in profile the base is in the form of the hieroglyph Maat; Thoth was closely connected with Maat in the daily ordering of the world's affairs.

description.value: Terracotta ithyphallic Harpocrates figure. A naked youth, modelled in the round, standing bandy-legged and holding his colossal phallus to himself, the glans resting on top of his head; the bulging object below the root of the phallus is presumably his testicles. He looks to his right, and wears a side-lock on his otherwise shaven head. At the rear of the figure a round-bottomed pot with a wide rim is placed on its side just below his head. The figure is supported by a low truncated-oval plinth, hollowed out below. Solid; two-piece mould. Micaceous Nile silt varying from dark brown to brown.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Beset, suckling the infant Bes.   A lamp modelled as Beset seated in a basket, suckling a child Bes. She wears a fringed Isis-mantle, opened to bare her left breast. Her hair is parted in the centre and falls onto her shoulders, and she wears a large wreath curving down from the top of her head to each side, with a narrow wreath-fillet crossing from side-to-side and held by ribbons at each end. Surmounting all is her feathered headdress. The Bes-child is naked except for his feathered headdress. There is a possibility that the basket is in fact the rope bindings of a mass of olives to be pressed. Below the basket is a curved high plain plinth pierced by two wick-holes with applied rests below each; the lamp has been used, as signs of burning show. The back is plain, except for a pierced suspension-lug behind Beset’s head, and a filling-hole for the oil-chamber, with a crescent-shaped guide below it.   Hollow; two-piece mould, with an inserted floor for the oil-chamber. Micaceous brown to red-brown Nile silt. Red slip applied to the front.
